&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Written evidence submitted by Classic FM [FBB0090][bold]&#xa0;
[normal]INTRODUCTION
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]This paper 
[normal]should be seen in conjunction with a submission from Global Radio. 
[normal]It focuses on the future of the BBC with regard to BBC Radio
[normal] 
[normal]3 and its exceptional role in broadcasting and commissioning classical music. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]BBC Radio 3 holds a unique position in the British broadcasting landscape. Its strength in the past has been in its ability to use this unique position, with the safety net of generous public funding, to create bold, distinctive, brave programming, unfette
[normal]red by the need to deliver audiences to advertisers. With a guaranteed income from the Licence Fee, BBC Radio 3 operates in common with other BBC services, without any fear of commercial failure. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Alone among any BBC radio or television service, it can be
[normal] argued that BBC Radio 3’s uniquely guaranteed funding, along with the concentration of power in the hands of the station’s Controller, is unprecedented in any other area of broadcasting or the arts in the UK. Not only is this role editorially and financia
[normal]lly responsible for the radio network, but the holder of the post is also the largest commissioner of classical music in the UK, controls the UK’s biggest live classical music festival (The BBC Proms) and is responsible for the five BBC Orchestras and the 
[normal]BBC Singers. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The 
[normal]position of 
[normal]BBC 
[normal]Radio
[normal] 
[normal]3 in the marketplace means that the 
[normal]BBC occupies a potentially market-distorting role in terms of the commissioning, broadcast and promotion of live classical music in the UK, either on radio or via digital online b
[normal]roadcasts. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The BBC must have great regard for the impact of 
[normal]BBC 
[normal]Radio
[normal] 
[normal]3 on the market place and on the classical music eco-system in the UK. In future, 
[normal]the BBC should enforce far tighter content requirements on publicly subsidised services such as BBC Ra
[normal]dio 3, with far greater regard to the overall competitive broadcast marketplace when programming changes are made. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Any incursions into digital delivery of classical music by the BBC – either via Radio 3 or through other means should be closely monitored 
[normal]and controlled. 
[normal]At present, these appear to be unfettered. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We would also welcome a new funding mechanism, which allows a far wider dissemination of classical music content from orchestras funded by the Arts Council. This could be through a public service fund, provided by a proportion of the licence fee, which all
[normal]ows commercial services to broadcast cultural events (such as live classical music concerts). This mechanism would ensure that these events reach a far wider audience, thereby making the ratio of public subsidy to audience reached far more economically jus
[normal]tifiable. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]By way of background, t
[normal]his submission
[normal] examines 
[normal]the effect of 
[normal]recent programme changes at BBC Radio 3. It will argue that although each of these changes may on its own be regarded as being 
[normal]relatively 
[normal]minor, 
[normal]when taken 
[normal]cumulatively over 
[normal]a 
[normal]sustain
[normal]ed period, they have 
[normal]profoundly affect
[normal]ed
[normal] both the character and the content of BBC Radio 3’s service.
[normal] In the process, this has resulted in a significant change to the classical music ra
[normal]dio landscape in the UK, with the serious
[normal] erosion of listener choice 
[normal]in
[normal] key dayparts 
[normal]being the principal outcome. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As a radio station that primarily broadcasts classical music, BBC Radio 3 operates in a market of two, with Classic FM its commercial radio competitor. 
[normal]These significant changes by BBC Radio 3 have the potential
[normal] to radically alter the classical music radio marketplace in the UK
[normal] to the detriment of its commercial rival
[normal].
[normal] As yet, the BBC Trust has refused formally to examine the impact of these changes. 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Given the amount of public money available to BBC Radio 3’s management, it is imperative that this funding is invested to augment and widen the artistic depth and breadth of classical music broadcasting in the UK, rather than in replicating the service alr
[normal]eady provided by Classic FM, the BBC’s only commercial competitor in this area. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]According to BBC Radio 3’s Service Licence, issued by the BBC Trust in July 2011:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]The remit of Radio 3 is to offer a mix of music and cultural programming in order to engag
[normal]e and entertain its audience… Radio 3’s programmes should exhibit some or all of the following characteristics: high quality, original, challenging, innovative and engaging, and it should nurture UK talent… The service should aim to educate audi
[normal]ences about
[normal] music, broadcasting a
[normal] wide range of programmes that expose listeners to new and sometimes challenging material they may not otherwise experience.
[normal]”[bold] 
[normal]PROGRAMMING CHANGES
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The past few years have seen a series of major programming changes to the style and content of BBC Radio 3’s output. 
[normal]These changes have not been introduced all at once in one bold move. Rather, it is apparent that there has been a creeping 
[normal]popularisation
[normal] o
[normal]f BBC Radio 3’s output
[normal] over the past few years
[normal], with the effect that
[normal] the clear 
[normal]gap between it and Classic FM has been
[normal] gradually eroded, with the BBC station moving inexorably towards the position which has traditionally been occupied by its commercial comp
[normal]etitor. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]These 
[normal]changes 
[normal]have included (but are not limited to):
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]RESPONSES TO BBC RADIO 3’s OUTPUT CHANGES
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]In its Service Review of BBC Radio 3, published in April 2011, the BBC Trust says:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]We are aware that there are ways in which Radio 3 could more actively target new 
[normal]listeners. In particular, it could pursue a far more populist approach by abandoning its commitment to a wide range of challenging music, or by playing much shorter excerpts of orchestral pieces. However, such an approach would significantly jeopardise and
[normal] damage those elements that make Radio 3 distinctive and highly valued. Such a strategy would not be welcomed by either audiences or industry.
[normal]”[bold] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Although it is clear to those intimately involved in classical music broadcasting 
[normal]that the character and conte
[normal]nt of BBC R
[normal]adio 3’s output has 
[normal]in fact 
[normal]been creeping towards that of Classic FM over the 
[normal]past couple of years, this 
[normal]has now been noticed both by the 
[normal]wider 
[normal]listening public and by cultural commentators.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Voice of the Listener and Viewer says:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]We 
[normal]consider that Radio 3 needs to be highly distinctive in comparison with Classic FM. At present the morning drive ti
[normal]me is often indistinguishable f
[normal]r
[normal]o
[normal]m the commercial station. The BBC should originate not copy.
[normal]”[bold] [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]On January 10
[normal]th
[normal] 2011, Nicholas de Jongh wrot
[normal]e in The Independent under the headline 
[normal]Radio 3 – Low-brow, lightweight and losing its way?
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]These days Radio 3 sometimes sounds as if intent on transforming itself into a superior version of Classic FM. The wretchedly low-brow three hours’ a night of li
[normal]steners’ requests during The Genius of Mozart festival sounds for the first ti
[normal]me as i
[normal]f the station were seriously dress-rehearsing to slip down-market.
[normal]”[bold] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]On October 5
[normal]th
[normal] 2011, Sarah Spilsbury from the listeners’ group Friends of Radio 3 wrote in The Guardian:
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]The BBC Trust agreed in February that Radio 3 must redouble its efforts to reach a “broader audience”. Indeed, for their recent report on the station’s performanc
[normal]e, they sought the views of the broader public – most of whom do not listen to the station. Having ascertained that the non-listeners find Radio 3 
[normal]‘slightly daunting at times’
[normal], Mr Wright has imported all the tricks of popular, downmarket broadcasting to he
[normal]lp win over a new audience…
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Perhaps it will attract Classic FM listeners. But should the BBC be using public funds to provide a competitive alternative to a commercial station which has already staked out the territory as its own? Classic FM needs those l
[normal]isteners to survive; the BBC does not. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In order to be less “intimidating”, Radio 3 has lowered its intellectual standards. Instead of critical insights, the guests, listeners, presenters, even performers, are encouraged to 
[normal]share personal feelings, memori
[normal]es and tastes. Musical anal
[normal]ysis
[normal] has been reduced to the occ
[normal]asional concert interval talk, t
[normal]he same truncated morsels of longer works are played and replayed.
[normal]”[bold] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Daily Telegraph reported on 1
[normal]st
[normal] September 2011 that:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]Radio 3 is facing a growing backlash
[normal] from listeners fed up with hearing the same pieces played repeatedly alongside an abundance 
[normal]of excerpts rather than entire works. Ardent classical music fans are becoming increasingly frustrated with the station’s attempts to appeal to the mass market by 
[normal]diluting its content. Online message boards and forums have been buzzing with disquiet from listeners unimpressed with the steady influx of celebrity presenters, the regular phone-ins and audience participation.
[normal]”[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Michael White wrote in the Daily Telegraph
[normal] on 3
[normal]rd
[normal] September 2011 under the headline 
[normal]“
[normal]Radio 3 is getting out of tune with its audience
[normal]”
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]In its search for that “wider public”, Radio 3 is edging ever closer to the comfortable banality of Classic FM. It uses celebrity presenters. It replaces inform
[normal]ed discussion with vacuous blather. It fills vast tracts of airtime with disc-jockey formats. It slips into Classic FM’s (commercially successful) routine of selling art as relaxation – as if Bach, Brahms and the other towering giants of music churned out 
[normal]all those notes for tired executives to sleep through. Needless to say, no one at Radio 3 would admit this. For them, Classic FM is the elephant in the room, its existence barely acknowledged, 
[normal]its influence denied. Roger Wright, the station’s controller, w
[normal]ill emphatically tell you that there’s no competition between the two, and no pressure for him to follow Classic’s lead. The truth is otherwise. Classic FM pulls an audience of around 5.7 million, while Radio 3 only manages 2.2 million. And that means pres
[normal]sure – which Wright has never resisted with the vigour that certain of his predecessors (especially John Drummond) managed.
[normal]”[bold] 
[normal]   
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]On 3
[normal]rd
[normal] October 2011, the Daily Telegraph radio critic Gillian Reynolds noted that
[normal]:
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
