[normal]WHAT DO RADIO 3 LISTENERS SAY?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Better to understand the views of BBC Radio 3’s listeners, Classic FM commissioned YouGov to undertake research with a p
[normal]anel of 1,086 Radio 3 
[normal]listeners at the end of March 2012.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]YouGov notes that there are clear indications in this research that 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]...
[normal]some listeners perceive that Radio 3 is becoming less specialised in its output and on occasion may be seen as imitating the output of oth
[normal]er sta
[normal]tions such as Classic FM.
[normal]”[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]YouGov adds:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]A
[normal]mong those dissatisfied with Radio 3, there appears to be a perception that presenters now try to cater for an audience with less sophisticated tastes and no longer try as hard to intellectu
[normal]ally challenge the 
[normal]audience.
[normal]”[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Radio 3’s remit is intended to extend far beyond being only a classical music station (unlike Classic FM, which only broadcasts classical music). However,
[normal] the researchers comment that:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]F
[normal]ew listeners associate Radio 3 with representing jazz, d
[normal]rama and religion well as part o
[normal]f its overall remit i.e. this is
[normal] the majority perception of where Radio 3 currently falls short. This implies that by over representing classical music, other, non-classical music based outputs are being und
[normal]er represented.
[normal]”[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Only 58% of Radio 3’s listeners regard the station as being “original” and just 48% say that it is “innovative”.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There is clear evidence in the research that Radio 3’s listeners believe that their station has recently moved closer to the output of Classi
[normal]c FM, thereby reducing the choice 
[normal]of styles of classical music radio stations 
[normal]available to them
[normal]:
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]Radio 3 listeners enjoy the notion that this radio station specialises in classical music and appeals to a niche group of listeners, further echoed by close
[normal] to 3 in 10 (29%) saying that the reason for their dissatisfaction is the dumbing down of content, trying to be more like Classic FM and
[normal] playing more well-known music.
[normal]”[bold]&#xa0;[bold]When YouGov questioned Radio 3 listeners specifically about the station’s programming 
[normal]output, clear areas of dissatisfaction become apparent:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]Around 1 in 4 listeners perceive that Radio 3 does not play enough specialist/rare recordings of classical music (24%) or live
[normal] classical music concerts (24%).
[normal]”[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]22% of listeners think that there ha
[normal]s been a decline in the amount of less well known classical music that is played now compared to 12 months ago, with this increasing to 56% of dissatisfied listeners. 39% of listeners think that there is more popular classic
[normal]al music being played (59% am
[normal]ong
[normal] those that clai
[normal]m that they will listen to less over the next 12 months and 64% among dissatisfied listeners), indicating a potential cause of their dissatisfaction.
[normal]”[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]A quarter of all listeners have said that they have noticed a change to the frequency with which popular classics are played on Radio 3. Of these listeners, 
[normal]86% claim that they are playing more popular classical music on Radio 3.
[normal]”[bold]&#xa0;[bold]“[bold]Amongst those less sati
[normal]sfied with Radio 3 now compared to 12 months ago, 56% say that the quality of less well known classical music is lower compared to 12 months ago, while 44% think that the quality of popular classical music is lower compared to 12 months ago and 23% think t
[normal]he quality for contemporary classical music is lower.
[normal]”[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]YouGov also looked at Radio 3 listeners’ perceptions of the station’s non-classical music output – an important part of the station’s remit. 50% of listeners fee
[normal]l that Radio 3 is representing R
[normal]eligion
[normal] poorly; 38% say feel that the station is representing Drama poorly; 31% believe th
[normal]at J
[normal]azz 
[normal]is represented
[normal] poorly; 
[normal]26% believe that W
[normal]orld Music is represented poorly; and 19% believe that Arts and Ideas are represented poorly.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]When it comes to the amount 
[normal]of non-classical music broadcast on Radio 3, 27% of listeners feel not enough Jazz is being played; 22% of listeners feel not enough World Music is being played; 21% believe not enough Drama is being broadcast; 20% believe not enough Literature is featured
[normal] and 19% believe that there is not enough Educational Content on the station. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As part of YouGov’s research into the BBC Radio 3 audience
[normal] carried out in March 2012
[normal], the station’s listeners were offered t
[normal]he opportunity to make open-ended 
[normal]observations about
[normal] the station’s programming. Many of these centred on the perception that BBC Radio 3’s output had moved towards th
[normal]at of its commercial competitor:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]In trying to appeal more to the traditional Classic FM listener, you’re alienating a lot of your dedicated listeners. I know a lot of people who used to listen to Radio 3 through most of the day and now regularly turn it off 
[normal]when it becomes too populist
[normal].
[normal]”[bold]&#xa0;[bold]“[bold]Stop trying to copy other radio stations. Radio 3 stood out from the rest a few years ago. Why do you feel the need to imitate Classic FM or Radio 2? I deliberately choose Radio 3 over Classic FM. Stop worrying about ratings and put the money into what y
[normal]ou do best.
[normal]”[bold]&#xa0;[bold]“[bold]Go back to being a station specialising in authoritative ways of playing and talking about classical music, and stop all the dumbing down.
[normal]”[bold]&#xa0;[bold]“[bold]More excerpts rather than fuller pieces. Radio 3 should not try to become Classic FM.
[normal]”[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]THE BBC TR
[normal]UST’S RESPONSE TO RADIO 3’s CHANGES
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The BBC Management’s decision to make these changes 
[normal]- and 
[normal]the BBC Trust’s decision to wave them thr
[normal]ough - has
[normal], in each case, served to reduce the choice of listening available to audiences.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The BBC Trust’s Service 
[normal]Review of
[normal] BBC Radio 3, published in February
[normal] 2011, admits that:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]…over recent years, BBC management has made changes to Radio 3 in order to make the station more accessible and welcoming to potential listeners, particularly in peak-time slots (breakfast a
[normal]nd drive) as these are the key entry points for potential listeners.
[normal]”[bold] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However, we would argue that BBC Radio 3’s management is plotting a course
[normal] firmly towards the increasing
[normal] popularisation of the service and a dilution of its core public service output.
[normal] Crucially, these changes erode the choice available to listeners.  This view was echoed in submissions to the BBC Trust’s Service Review consultation by the Friends of Radio 3, 
[normal]by 
[normal]the Voice of the Listener and Viewer, and 
[normal]by 
[normal]the Incorporated Society of Mu
[normal]sicians. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The BBC Trust acknowledged that:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]BBC management…has changed the nature of the programmes during these hours.
[normal]”[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Although, the BBC Trust then goes on to describe this as:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]“[bold]Legitimate.
[normal]”[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]We 
[normal]disagree. T
[normal]he cumulative effect of the 
[normal]alterations 
[normal]made to BBC Radio 3’s output, 
[normal]when taken collectively
[normal], constitute a significant change to the service
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Under its own rules, the BBC Trust should have undertaken a Public Value Test, includ
[normal]ing a market impact assessment before allowing BBC Management to und
[normal]ertake such a radical overhaul of one of its national networks. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is clear from the responses to BBC Radio 3’s programming outlined above 
[normal](and there are many, many more similar – and some rather more trenchant – views in chatrooms online) that the liste
[normal]ning public, critics and
[normal] commentators have
[normal] taken a very differen
[normal]t view of these changes than that put forward by
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]BBC Trust.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Rather than pushing for BBC Radio 3 to maintain its distinctiveness, the BBC Trust’s Service Review instead appears to have a
[normal]ctively encouraged Radio 3 to become 
[normal]more [bold]like Classic FM. 
[normal]In
[normal] a market of 
[normal]just 
[normal]two 
[normal]classical music radio stations in the UK, the BBC has significantly changed the output on Radio 3 in pursuit of audiences, rather than with the aim of offering distinctive and original programming content. This lessening of distinctiveness is particula
[normal]rly stark in the key morning dayparts, when listening to classical music on the radio reaches the largest number of people. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Back in 1992, 
[normal]Classic FM introduced a new way of broadcasting classical music on UK radio. It complemented the style and content o
[normal]f BBC Radio 3’s output at the time, providing a real point of difference. Given Classic FM’s success in building audiences for classical music radio, 
[normal]twenty years later, 
[normal]the BBC now appears to have decided to ape its commercial co
[normal]mpetitor, abandoning much 
[normal]of the
[normal] distinctiveness in peak
[normal]-
[normal]time
[normal] 
[normal]hours in the process. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]No doubt, BBC Management will point to BBC Radio 3’s commitment to specialist off-peak programming, but 
[normal]by so starkly changing
[normal] 
[normal]BBC Radio 3’s programming to that of
[normal] a ‘ratings by day, reputation by
[normal] night’ strategy in a market place
[normal] of 
[normal]just 
[normal]two, repres
[normal]e
[normal]n
[normal]ts a potentially serious threat to the ability of Classic FM to operate 
[normal]as an 
[normal]effective commercial competitor. Classic FM is virtually unique in the classical music world in never having received a pe
[normal]nny of public subsidy to fund its work; it also does not enjoy the certainty of a fixed income from the Licence Fee. 
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Not only did the BBC Trust fail to implement a Public Value Test
[normal] into the BBC Management’s changes to Radio 3’s output
[normal], but it also fai
[normal]led to abide by its own ‘Competitive Impact Policy’, which requires the BBC ‘to minimise its negative competitive impacts on the wider market’.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The BBC Trust is obliged under the terms of the BBC Agreement with DCMS to undertake a Public Value Test before
[normal] a decision is taken to make a significant ch
[normal]ange to a BBC service. Although this is a decision for the Trust, the BBC Agreement requires the Trust before exercising its judgement to ‘investigate or otherwise inform itself of any facts or considerations wh
[normal]ich it considers potentially relevant’.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It appears that no such investigation took place. 
[normal]RadioCentre 
[normal]requested further detail 
[normal]from the BBC 
[normal]on the proposed strategy to make Radio 3 more accessible and welcoming under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 
[normal](Letter, 24
[normal]th
[normal] February, 2011). In its re
[normal]s
[normal]ponse to the request, the BBC said:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]The BBC did not undertake a significance assessment of making Radio 3 more accessible and welcoming. This is because it is not a new proposal, but ‘business as usual’: BBC Manag
[normal]ement has been seeking for some time to make its content more accessible and welcoming, and will continue to strive to do so. As such, no significance assessment was required.
[normal]”[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]This would suggest that the BBC Trust did not believe that a Public Value Test
[normal] was appropriate because the change
[normal]s made to BBC Radio 3 took place 
[normal]over a period of time, rather than at one single moment. However, the BBC Trust’s own protocols state that:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“[bold]A series of minor changes to a service licence may, cumulatively, require the 
[normal]Trust to consider whether a further regulatory approvals process, such as a Public Value Test, is required.
[normal]”[bold] 
[normal]              
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Not only should a Public Value Test have been undertaken, but also in failing to undertake a ‘significance assessment’ at all, the BBC Trust did
[normal] not abide by the terms of the BBC Agreement with DCMS. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There must be an overhaul of how BBC radio services are held accountable for their remit. As set out in the submission fr
[normal]om
[normal] our parent company, Global Radio, a new set of duties that take precedence
[normal] over the BBC’s public purposes will ensure BBC services do not encroach on their private sector competitors. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]BBC 
[normal]Radio 3, along with all BBC radio services, must have a tighter remit in future for which management are accountable. This new remit must re
[normal]assert 
[normal]BBC 
[normal]Radio
[normal] 
[normal]3’s duty to play specialist music throughout the schedule and ensure that the station does not duplicate content available on commercial services. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A CHANGE OF BRAND POSITIONING
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Classic FM’s pure classical music proposition has been highly successful in building new audiences for the genre. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As the 
[normal]BBC 
[normal]Radio 3 programming output continues 
[normal]to be allowed 
[normal]gradually to creep away from its responsibilities to non-classical music genre
[normal]s and peak
[normal]-
[normal]time
[normal] 
[normal]coverage of speech-based arts programme, the station now appears to be publicly acknowledging this move for the first time in its brand proposition.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]During 2013, it has 
[normal]changed its brand strapline to ‘The Home of Classical Music’
[normal]. Gone is 
[normal]any mention of other cultural or arts activities from its public-facing messaging.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This move in itself is worthy of investigation by the BBC Trust. Sadly, once again, the Trustees do not appear to be concerned about 
[normal]BBC 
[normal]Radio 3’s downgrading of the statio
[normal]n’s responsibilities to support wider arts and cultural programming. Once again, it appears that 
[normal]BBC 
[normal]Radio 3 is being encouraged to use its public funding to chase ratings b
[normal]y broadcasting classical music, which is well served by a commercial competitor
[normal], at
[normal] the expense of the promotion of other music genres, which are not well-served by the commercial radio sector. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]A QUESTION OF COST[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Yet further significant changes to BBC Radio 3’s programming output 
[normal]were discussed
[normal] in the 
[normal]Delivering Quality First 
[normal]document, which was published by the BBC in October 2011. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]These include
[normal]d
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Each of these changes represents a furth
[normal]er dilution of the essence that makes BB
[normal]C Radio 3’s output distinctive from that of Classic FM. These changes further compound the radical nature of programming changes to the station. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Given these 
[normal]fu
[normal]rther changes to BBC Radio 3
[normal]’s output and the public re
[normal]sponse to the changes, which have already taken place, it would be an appropriate moment for the BBC Trust to follow the procedures which it itself put in place and to undertake a full Public Value Test
[normal] at the earliest opportunity
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The latest round of 
[normal]programming changes have been blamed on the need for the BBC to reduce costs. However, an analysis of the BBC’s annual report suggests that BBC Radio 3
[normal] has an annual programme content 
[normal]budget of £38.3 million
[normal]. 
[normal]It additionally spends £5.3 million on distribu
[normal]tion, with a further £10.7 million spent on infrastructure and support. The BBC defines this latter figure as including: Property; HR; Policy and Strategy; Finance and Operations; and Marketing. It is important to note that these figures do not include the
[normal] cost of newsgathering or of BBC Radio 3’s online digital services, which are accounted for separately. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The BBC orchestras and performing groups receive total funding of £23.4 million per annum for content, with a further £5.8 million of infrastructure a
[normal]nd support funding. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]When added together, BBC Radio 3 and the BBC orchestras and performing groups spend £61.7 million on content, £5.3 million on distribution and £16.5 million on infrastructure and support – giving a grand total of £83.5 million of expe
[normal]nditure in the 2012-13 financial year – an increase of 
[normal]£2 million on the previous year. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This is a huge amount of money. 
[normal]BBC 
[normal]Radio 3 cited the need to cut costs as the reason for the reduction in its commitment to specialist music programming from Septemb
[normal]er 2013. However, given the scale of public money at 
[normal]BBC 
[normal]Radio 3’s disposal, there must surely be concern that the service is operating with a huge level of inefficiency for it not to be able to contain overall costs at a level that allowed these programme
[normal]s to continue. 
[normal]For this to be the case, we find it hard to believe that the stringent cost controls that would be in place in the commercial sector – out of commercial necessity - can possibly be being applied to a service that relies on a high level of gu
[normal]aranteed public subsidy via the Licence Fee. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It should also be noted that the live classical music market place already sees publicly funded orchestras in the geographic regions where the BBC funds additional orchestras. This is particularly the case in 
[normal]London, Manchester and Glasgow
[normal], where it could be argued that the Licence Fee duplicates provision already funded via Arts Council England and the Scottish Government. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]THE CONCENTRATION OF POWER[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Nowhere in the broadcasting or the arts world does
[normal] so much power to spend such a large amount of public money rest in the hands of a single individual.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Controller of Radio 3 is responsible for the UK’s biggest broadcaster of live classical music; the biggest commissioner of classical music; the UK’s 
[normal]biggest classical music festival (the BBC Proms); and responsibility for no fewer than five orchestras. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To concentrate so much power in the hands of one individual
[normal] 
[normal]has the potential to create
[normal] an abuse of 
[normal]this market dominant position.
[normal] 
[normal]We 
[normal]remain concerned
[normal] that this does not represent
[normal] 
[normal]the best
[normal] system for
[normal] stewardship of a significa
[normal]nt amount of licence fee money – and nor is it in the best interests o
[normal]f creating a plural and diverse classical music ecosystem in the UK. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]L
[normal]icence 
[normal]funding in this area 
[normal]should be 
[normal]open to competition 
[normal]to enable commercial operators to broadcast
[normal] classical music concerts
[normal] that are already funded or subsidised through Arts Council investment, perhaps through the creation of a ‘public service content publisher’ model, funded by a proporti
[normal]on of the licence fee.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Additionally, we are concerned that the creation in 2012 of The Space by the BBC and the Arts Council effectively creates a new publicly funded BBC service by the backdoor, without the usual checks and balances that are applied to the introduction of a new
[normal] BBC channel. This 
[normal]introduces 
[normal]a new level of 
[normal]publicly subsidised 
[normal]competition to the classical music broadcasting marketplace that did not previously ex
[normal]ist. Given the move towards wider digital distribution of radio services, a brand new online channel supp
[normal]or
[normal]ted through Licence Fee funding
[normal] should not be regarded in isolation, but should be seen as being a part of the overall media marketplace. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]CONCLUSION[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]BBC 
[normal]Radio
[normal] 
[normal]3 offers a unique service
[normal], which adds enormous value on the occasions that it broadcasts content that is not served well by its commercial competitor. 
[normal]In these instances, it is a cultural gem which is rightly cherished – and which is deserving of its significant public funding.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]H
[normal]owever, t
[normal]here is clear evidence that programming changes to BBC Radio 3 cumulatively constitute a significant alteration to the station’s on-air output
[normal] which is undermining listener choice and value for money for the licence fee payer
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This view is not only held by 
[normal]Classic FM and its parent company, 
[normal]Global Radio. It has been commented upon widely in the press and both quantitative and qualitative independent research supports this assertion.
[normal] Indeed, the view that 
[normal]BBC 
[normal]Radio 3’s output now
[normal] apes that of Classic FM for much of the day has reached a crescendo. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Beyond 2016, a new set of public duties for the BBC and a new remit for 
[normal]BBC 
[normal]Radio
[normal] 
[normal]3 must reverse and prevent further incursion of the service into commercial, populist territory. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Fai
[normal]lure to do so would allow BBC Management to continue to manoeuvre BBC Radio 3 away from its core remit, supported by the privilege 
[normal]of its generous public funding, further towards that of its commercial competitor.
[normal] In future, station management must be held
[normal] to account for a more detailed remit focused on delivering distinct public service content. To carry on as now 
[normal]would result in further erosion in listener choice and the UK’s broadcasting landscape would be the poorer for it. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We would encourage the C
[normal]ult
[normal]ure, Media and Sport Select C
[normal]ommittee
[normal] 
[normal]to examine ways in which these issues can be both monitored and controlled as 
[normal]any new funding agreement
[normal] is negotiated. 
[normal]It is clear that the existing control mechanisms are both inadequate and open to abuse. 
[normal]&#xa0;
